<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-89 0022EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua-Godoy     09-03 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Godoy,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experienced Politician Chosen As Opposition Running Mate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virgilio Godoy Reyes brings solid
political experience and a controversial personality to the campaign
for which he is running as opposition vice presidential candidate in
next February's election.
   While crowds at the headquarters of the National Opposition Union
on Saturday night cheered Violeta Barrios de Chamorro, the
presidential candidate, hecklers three times shouted the name of
Godoy's rival for the No. 2 spot.
   While perhaps not an auspicious start for a political candidate,
Godoy's strong personality _ which some have described as arrogant
and abrasive _ can take the heckling.
   The hostility stems from his four-year, eight-month tenure as
Labor Minister under the leftist Sandinista government, against
which he is running now. As Labor Minister, Godoy instituted a
system of salary levels that became widely unpopular. Detractors say
his government post also makes his allegiance to the opposition
somewhat suspect.
   Godoy was Labor Minister from July 19, 1979 to March 31, 1984,
when he resigned. He said later that he quit because he disagreed
with the leftist Sandinista ideology. His resignation however
reflects his political talent _ the government gave him a going-away
reception, showing he must have left in good stead.
   The 55-year-old lawyer has been better at defending himself from
power plays within his own party, the Independent Liberals, than in
attacking the Sandinistas.
   Political attacks against Godoy stem not only from his
personality as from his tenure as president of the Independent
Liberal Party for 10 years. One critic, who prefered to remain
unidentified, called Godoy ``dictatorial and Machiavellian.''
   Godoy follows a long tradition of Liberalism in his family. His
grandfather, Gen. Paulino Godoy, was the spearhead of the
Nicaragua's Liberal revolution of 1983.
   He has said that the slogan of the French revolution, ``Liberty,
Equality, Brotherhood,'' encapsules the most important concepts for
the individual and society.
   Godoy is married to Sonia Perez Mercado, a Mexican; they have
three children.
</TEXT>
