<FIRST>u a BC-VaBeachRiot 1stLd-Writethru a0638 09-03 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Va Beach Riot, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0638,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two People Shot, Over 100 Stores Looted in Va Beach Rioting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Rewrites throughout to UPDATE with resort strip closed, add
quotes, other detail. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rioting broke out early Sunday in this
resort city, and more than 100 downtown stores were looted and at
least two people shot before a National Guard military police
attachment was deployed, authorities said.
   Diane Roche, assistant director of public information for
Virginia Beach, said guardsmen were called out by Gov. Gerald L.
Baliles shortly after 4 a.m. to assist local authorities. She did
not have exact figures on the number of guardsmen involved.
   She said the rioting began around 2 a.m. when police confronted a
mob on Atlantic Avenue, the main beachfront thoroughfare.
   She had no estimate on the crowd size or what may have set off
the rioting.
   City Manager Aubrey V. Davis ordered much of the resort strip
closed, and residents were told to avoid the area.
   An estimated more than 25,000 college students from predominantly
black schools up and down the East Coast are in town for the annual
Greekfest. Roche said she didn't know if the riot was related to the
gathering.
   Police reported at least four injuries, including the two men
shot. Roche was unable to identify any of the injured or say what
their condition was. She said police officers were not involved in
the shootings.
   Police reported scattered gunfire and several fires in the area
overnight.
   Davis said police, backed by state troopers and the National
Guard, were in ``crowd control positions'' in the oceanfront area.
   At 7 a.m., the area was reported quiet.
   Brenda Kanz, front desk manager at the Kona Kai Motel, said
authorities were not allowing anyone to leave the hotel ``even for
breakfast'' unless they were checking out to go home. Many college
students were staying at the motel, and they remained in their rooms
while guardsmen and police patrolled the streets, she said.
   ``It's a heck of a way to end the season,'' she said.
   Dan Bremer, desk clerk at the Kona Kai East two blocks away, said
some families were checking out of the motel early. He said cash
registers from nearby stores had been hurled into the street by
looters.
   ``It's pretty messy,'' he said.
</TEXT>
