<DOCNO> AP890903-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-89 1345EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Vietnam     09-03 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Leader Stands Firm Against Democratic Reform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnamese leader Nguyen Van Linh
sharply rejected a multi-party system for his Communist nation and
declared that freedom of speech amounts to anarchy.
   Expressing unease with the kind of changes sweeping the Soviet
Union, Poland, and other Communist countries, Linh said Vietnam
would keep liberalizing its economy but not its political system.
   ``It is not our policy to hasten renovation of the political
system while preparations are still inadequate,'' the Communist
Party leader said. ``Neither is it our intention to effect limitless
democratization.''
   ``The Communist Party of Vietnam is the leader, initiator and
pacesetter in renovation,'' Linh said. ``We shall not allow any
force to set up any opposition party to work against the people and
against socialism. Once again, we declare that we resolutely reject
pluralism, a multi-party system or opposition parties.''
   His comments came in a 10,000-word speech laden with Marxist
terminology and dogma. Linh, an economic reformer who has also taken
some steps toward political liberalization, gave the address at a
meeting in Hanoi on Friday to mark Vietnam's National Day. A text
was seen in Bangkok on Sunday.
   Its basic thrust reflected a recent conservative trend in Hanoi,
with official media lashing out at liberal reform in Hungary and
Poland.
   Some observers believe the trend stems from leaders' fears that
Vietnam's ``open-door'' economic policy will lead to a popular
pro-democracy movement such as occurred in China.
   Others, however, believe the recent conservative declarations are
a tactical ploy by party liberals to appease conservative elements.
   ``Democracy does not mean that one is free to say what one wants
to say, write what one wants to write and do what one wants to do,
no matter what the consequences may be,'' the Communist leader said.
``These are essentially anarchist acts.''
   Linh said that while Vietnam believes in the reform occurring in
some Communist countries, there were ``opposition forces of all
colors which are misusing liberalization and openness to fish in
troubled waters.''
   He accused the United States and other ``imperialists'' of trying
to undermine the Communist camp and launching ``frenzied attacks
against socialism.''
   However, Linh said capitalist-style reforms would continue in
Vietnam. He said the pace of such changes has quickened considerably
since they were first launched two years ago.
</TEXT>
