<FIRST>r a AM-FireApology     09-03 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fire Apology,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>At Court's Behest, Four Whites Appear in Black Church to Apologize
for Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADAIRVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four white people who set fire to a church
founded by freed slaves returned to the newly renovated building to
give their court-ordered apologies to the congregation.
   Bill Sircy, 22, bowed his head and cleared his throat during
Saturday's dedication of the new Smith Grove AME Zion Church, then
said, ``We're sorry, but I know that's not enough.''
   The congregation of about 60 people responded, ``Amen!''
   ``What we did was wrong,'' said Angela B. Estep, whose husband
stood nearby. ``It was an accident, but it was still wrong. And I'm
sorry.''
   As Sherri Davenport, 19, spoke, her grandfather, Herman England
of Adairville, listened from the church doorway. Afterward he said
he was proud of her courage in taking responsibility for her action.
   ``What's done is done; they can't bring it back,'' England said.
``But they did what they could.''
   Danny Smith, 22, echoed that sentiment after the service. ``There
just wasn't a whole lot we could say _ just that we're sorry.''
   The congregation gave the four young people a round of applause
as they left the church.
   ``I think what they did was a fantastic gesture,'' said Sarah
Garrick of Chicago, who grew up near the church.
   ``We are just amazed that this type of thing could happen,'' said
Ms. Garrick, 57. ``When I lived here, this would have never have
happened because of the racial prejudices in the area. I think it's
wonderful that the court made them come out here and apologize.''
   Last October the four young people, all residents of this rural
western Kentucky town, pleaded guilty in Logan District Court to
breaking into the 116-year-old church and setting it on fire in May
1986.
   Before their sentencing, the four had paid $6,000 to rebuild the
church, and prosecutors agreed to amend the charges from felonies to
misdemeanors. But when Logan District Judge Dale L. Prince sentenced
them, he ordered them to apologize to the congregation of face
contempt of court, with possibly a year in jail and a $500 fine.
   Prince also put each of the four on probation for two years.
</TEXT>
