<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh     09-03 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nationwide Strike By Rival Groups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shops, banks and schools closed and
armed police patrolled the streets Sunday during a nationwide strike
called by opposition groups.
   Except for a few rickshaws, the streets of Dhaka and other major
cities were deserted and many government and private offices closed
during the six-hour strike, witnesses said.
   Strike supporters in small groups paraded through downtown Dhaka,
chanting slogans, deflating rickshaw tires and harrassing rickshaw
pullers, witnesses said. At least 16 people were arrested, police
said.
   Baton-wielding police clashed with members of a procession near a
mosque in central Dhaka, police and witnesses said. About 20 people,
including two opposition leaders, were slightly injured, they said.
   In downtown Dhaka, a gasoline bomb was thrown at a jeep taking
two policewomen to work. The jeep exploded and the two women jumped
to the street, police said.
   One officer, an inspector at the department's special
intelligence branch, suffered severe head injuries and was in a
coma, police said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   An eight-party opposition alliance headed by the Awami League
called the strike to protest an Aug. 10 attack by unidentified
gunmen on the home of the Awami League chief Sheikh Hasina.
   No one was injured in the attack, blamed on the Freedom Party
whose leaders plotted the violent 1975 coup that toppled the
government of Mrs. Hasina's father, Sheik Mujibur Rahman.
   Party leaders denied any involvement the attack and called a
strike demanding a ban on the Awami League and its allies.
   Hasina and another opposition leader, Khaleda Zia, have been
leading a 6-year-old campaign against the government of President
Hussain Muhammad Ershad, who seized power in a military coup in
March 1982. They are demanding Ershad's resignation and new
elections.
</TEXT>
