<FIRST>r a AM-ColliderQuarrel     09-03 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Collider Quarrel,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Towns Feud Over Super Collider Fame</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAXAHACHIE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The superconducting super collider
project has got three towns on a super collision course over
bragging rights to the giant atom smasher, bringing out their big
artillery on billboards and bumper stickers.
   All three _ Waxahachie, Ennis and Midlothian _ want people to
think of their town first when they think of the collider which is
slated for Ellis County and, in fact, won't touch any of the three.
   The fight isn't quite so heated as the battle that preceded it,
when politicians all over the country sought to get the
multibillion-dollar federal project in their state. Instead, it's a
battle fought with bumper stickers and billboards.
   Ennis proclaims itself ``Super Collider Country'' and Midlothian
boasts it's the ``Gateway to the Super Collider.''
   So far, Waxahachie has smashed the competition. At 18,150 people,
it is the biggest town in Ellis County and will be encircled by the
53-mile collider ring. It calls itself ``The Center of Attention,
Home of the super collider.''
   The other two towns are on the outskirts of the ring, which is to
be built in the country south of Dallas-Fort Worth.
   Shortly after the U.S. Energy Department announced in November
that Ellis County would be the collider site, the Waxahachie Chamber
of Commerce printed hundreds of bumper stickers proclaiming itself
the center.
   The town also rented billboard space off Interstate 35 to carry
the same message.
   That was enough to make officials in Ennis and Midlothian stomp
in protest.
   Ennis, a town of about 14,150 people east of Waxahachie,
countered with its own boast on a billboard on Interstate 45.
   ``The only thing Waxahachie has is its name,'' said Kipp Burnett,
executive vice president of the Ennis Chamber of Commerce. ``It
sticks. Even though it's hard to say, you don't forget it.''
   Bob Sokoll, Waxahachie city manager, scoffs at such talk.
   ``We are not going to let one peon city to the east like Ennis
think they are the home of the super collider,'' Sokoll said. ``The
only thing Ennis does better than us is play football.''
   Midlothian, population 5,000, won't be left out, said Pam Mundo,
executive director of the town's chamber of commerce. She's the one
who came up with the slogan: ``We are the Gateway to the Super
Collider.''
   The Texas National Research Laboratory Commission, the state
agency in charge of acquiring the land for the collider, is shying
away from the feud.
   ``We have tried not to get caught up in the local competition,''
commission spokeswoman Catherine Burns said last week. ``We have
always referred to the super collider as being in Ellis County.''
   Ground has not been broken for the colossal project, but
officials say it should be operational by 1996.
   The collider is expected to reveal new information about the
nature of matter and the origins of the universe. It will hurl
minute beams of protons toward one another inside a 53-mile tunnel.
It is expected to create 4,000 temporary construction jobs and 3,000
permanent positions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
