<FIRST>r i AM-Finland-Hungary     09-03 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Finland-Hungary,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grosz Rules Out Force By Hungarian Communists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungarian Communist Party chief Karoly
Grosz promised that the party will not use force to hold onto power
if it loses the nation's first multi-party elections next year, a
newspaper reported Sunday.
   In an interview by the daily Helsingin Sanomat newspaper, Grosz
acknowledged that Hungarian communists want to wield power.
   However, he added that the party would ``draw its own
conclusions'' if it were to lose the elections, due to be held at
the latest in 1990, according to the paper.
   ``We would not be satisfied with such a situation,'' Grosz was
quoted as saying. However, he ruled out using force as a political
weapon, saying, ``We would not use tanks but political arguments to
get back into power.''
   He said he will step down as party general secretary during a
party congress on Oct. 6, but that he would continue to be active in
politics. ``I want to remain in the party leadership,'' he said.
   In Finland, Grosz was scheduled to meet with President Mauno
Koivisto on Monday.
   Grosz's power was diluted in June when party reformers
established a ruling presidium with the general secretary as one of
four members. Party chairman Rezsoe Nyers has described himself as
``first among equals'' on the new body.
   In Hungary on Sunday, the reformers preparing for the party
congress clashed over how far to go in revamping the party.
   Presidium members Imre Pozsgay, Miklos Nemeth, and Nyers spoke at
a two-day conference of reformist communists held to plan strategy
for the October congress.
   Nyers told the nearly 400 delegates that the party's political
and economic policies must be revamped.
   However, Pozsgay went further, calling for a ``Copernican
revolution,'' invoking the Polish astronomer whose discovery that
the earth was round shook conservative-minded colleagues in the 16th
century.
   Nemeth, in comments Saturday, appeared still more radical. He
said ``dyed-in-the-wool Bolsheviks'' who cannot accept far-reaching
reforms should be free to split and form rival parties.
   Party Central Committee Secretary Gyoergy Fejti told a rally
Saturday that 10,000 members a month have been leaving the party in
the recent past. He said only 200 new members had been enrolling
each month.
   Since endorsing the idea of a multi-party democracy in February,
the Hungarian communists suffered upset defeats in three
parliamentary by-elections. The voting represented Hungary's freest
voting in over 40 years.
   Party reformers, who advocate a free-market economy in addition
to a pluralistic political system, hold views that often put them
closer to some non-communist opposition groups than to conservatives
in their own party.
</TEXT>
