<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     09-03 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanese Fighting Flares After 18-Hour Lull</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian forces fought with
artillery in Lebanon's central mountains on Sunday, shattering an
18-hour lull.
   Police said one person was killed and 11 were wounded in Sunday's
exchanges. The latest casualties raised the toll since the fighting
broke out March 8 to at least 826 killed and 2,449 wounded.
   Sunday's battle flared around the mountain town of Douar, one of
four routes into the besieged Christian heartland north of Beirut.
   The clashes, which ignited forest fires, occurred on the eastern
flank of the coastal enclave, ringed on its landward sides by the
Syrians and their Moslem allies.
   They have reportedly been massing their forces in recent days,
but they made no clear move to push into the Christian enclave
Sunday.
   Though Beirut has been battered nearly incessantly in the six
months of fighting, the capital was quiet during Sunday's clashes.
Christian and Moslem sectors of the city were hammered for 36 hours
between Thursday and Saturday, when at least 20 people were killed
and more than 100 wounded in one of the hardest-fought
Syrian-Christian duels.
   On Sunday, Syrian howitzers and mortars pounded Douar and the
resort towns of Kekfaya and Btighrin that are clustered around
twisting roads leading into Christian territory, where an estimated
1 million people are trapped.
   The Christian forces, led by Gen. Michel Aoun, retaliated by
hitting Syrian positions in the mountains with 155mm howitzer and
tank fire, police said.
   Pine woods burned out of control because firefighters could not
reach the battle zone northeast of Beirut, said a police spokesman
who cannot be identified under standing regulations.
   The rival forces also skirmished with machine guns and
truck-mounted 106mm recoilless guns around the mountaintop Christian
stronghold of Souk el-Gharb southeast of Beirut, the spokesman said.
   Aoun began the current round of a 14-year-old civil war by
blockading ports controlled by Moslem militias. He then declared a
``war of liberation'' to drive Syrian forces from Lebanon.
   The 40,000 Syrian troops came to Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League
peacekeeping mandate. However, Aoun says they are backing the Moslem
side in the civil war.
   The fighting has forced all but an estimated 150,000 of Beirut's
1.5 million population to flee their devastated city.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
