<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia-Glance     09-03 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Glance,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Military Aid To Colombia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here at a glance is President Bush's
emergency aid package to Colombia to help that government fight its
war against powerful cocaine cartels.
   __
   COST: $65 million.
   __
   EQUIPMENT: Two C-130B transport planes, five UH-1H transport
helicopters, eight A-37 reconnaissance and attack jets, and an
unspecified number of trucks, small boats, radios, grenade
launchers, machine guns, rifles, pistols, and other equipment. Also
bulletproof vests for Colombian judges and other officials who
attempt to prosecute suspected drug traffickers.
   __
   U.S. PERSONNEL _ Up to 200, although not necessarily all at the
same time, according to the Pentagon. Colombia has expressed
wariness about the presence of U.S. troops on its soil, and American
officials have been evasive in providing specific numbers.
   __
   DELIVERY _ The C-130s arrived Sunday, carrying some of the
smaller items in the package. The A-37s were due Monday, and the
helicopters on Tuesday. No specific schedule was announced for
completing the delivery.
</TEXT>
