<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-89 1618EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bauman-Frank     09-03 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bauman-Frank,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ousted Gay Congressman Urges Congress to go Slow on Judging Personal
Lives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gay former congressman, forced out of office
by a sex scandal nine years ago, came to the defense Sunday of
embattled Rep. Barney Frank, saying the Capitol Hill brouhaha sounds
all too familiar _ and could backfire.
   ``It has the strange familiarity of what Yogi Berra might have
called `deja vu all over again','' former Rep. Robert Bauman, a
Republican, wrote in a lengthy article in The Washington Post on the
current controversy involving Frank, a Democrat, and his
relationship with a male prostitute.
   Last month, Frank, who in 1987 acknowledged to being gay,
confirmed published reports that he had solicited and then
befriended a male prostitute, allowed him to use his Washington
apartment, and paid him $20,000 a year from private funds to do
various chores.
   The prostitute, Steven Gobie, claimed he operated a prostitution
service out of Frank's apartment and that the Massachusetts
congressman knew about it. Frank has denied any such knowledge and
despite the controversy recently received signs of continuing strong
support back in his home district.
   Bauman, a staunch conservative, had no such luck and was defeated
in his Maryland district in 1980, ending eight years in Congress
after it was revealed he was gay and had been arrested for
soliciting a male prostitute.
   Bauman wrote in the Sunday edition of the Post that he probably
would disagree with Frank, a liberal, on 95 percent of the issues
facing America and likely would not vote for him.
   ``But I surely would not vote against him for what happened with
the likes of Steve Gobie,'' Bauman wrote, chastising Gobie as a
``louse'' and a ``despicable character'' who thinks nothing of
turning on his ``former mentor'' for personal gain. Frank has said
he befriended Gobie because he wanted to help him recover from past
mistakes including a prison record.
   Referring to the possibility that Congress may move to censure or
reprimand Frank, Bauman, now a Washington lawyer, wrote:
   ``One thing I do know. The House of Representatives, both
collectively and individually, is not equipped to judge Barney Frank
in this matter. They may well decide to censure or reprimand him for
his private _ now very public _ past conduct, but they do so at
their own peril.
   ``This is not an easy case of Jim Wright venality. It is not a
case of a congressman taking advantage of a page boy or page girl.
It is a case involving consenting adults, one of whom happened to be
a congressman and the other a louse. And if such private acts become
the jurisdiction of Congress, the lines of the miscreants might as
well begin forming on the Right and the Left.''
   Bauman continued, ``While the media and the public might enjoy
the titillation of this incipient reign of terror, the end result
will be the decimation of government.''
   Bauman also urged against Frank resigning, saying the matter is
for the voters in his district to decide.
</TEXT>
