<FIRST>r i AM-Baltics     09-03 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baltics,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Rally on Baltic Shores to Protest Pollution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Baltic coast residents lined up
hand-in-hand on the seashore Sunday to protest pollution that they
say is killing the Baltic Sea, journalists and activists said.
   ``People want to bring attention to the fact that the sea is
dying,'' said Askolds Rodins, a translator at the Latvian People's
Front newspaper Atmoda. He was speaking in a telephone interview
from Riga, the Latvian republic's capital.
   Concern over pollution is widespread in Latvia, Estonia and
Lithuania, which also are homes of popular movements for greater
autonomy.
   Sunday's seaside protest was organized by the region's fledgling
Greens environmental movement.
   Many Baltic residents believe Moscow authorities have recklessly
built factories and plants that pollute the environment. They have
pressed for local control over polluters and economic resources.
   New measures beginning Jan. 1 will give Estonia and Latvia more
control over local factories.
   This year's anti-pollution demonstration was overshadowed by
other Baltic political events, journalists and activists said. An
Estonian Radio editor said thousands took to the beaches Sunday, but
the turnout was smaller than expected.
   ``There were so many events already, people are tired,'' said the
editor, who spoke on condition of anonymity in a telephone interview
from Tallinn, the Estonian capital.
   On Aug. 23, more than 1 million Baltic residents linked hands in
a giant human chain stretching across the three republics. The chain
was formed to protest the Hitler-Stalin pact that led to the Soviet
annexation of the Baltic nations.
</TEXT>
