<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-89 1625EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     09-03 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRISFIELD, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chopper, a small female Chesapeake
blue-claw crab, had to endure some rough pre-race handling but it
paid off as she scrambled to victory in the 42nd National Hard Crab
Derby.
   Jason Byrd, 14, owner of the winner, said throughbred crabs need
to be riled up to prepare for competition. His mother, Kathy Byrd,
said that was accomplished by taunting it with a stick for two hours
``to get it mangy.''
   Chopper survived a preliminary heat and beat 15 finalists
Saturday to top the field of 283.
   Jason said another key was that he caught his own entry instead
of using one furnished by race organizers.
   One race worker, however, said the real key is finding a lively,
small crab.
   ``A lot of people bring the big ones and think they are going to
win,'' said Glenn Stewart of Crisfield. ``But it's the little ones.''
   Participants, who paid $3, were assigned a crab or could enter
their own. Each crab had to finish in the top three of a preliminary
heat to qualify for the final.
   In the Governor's Cup, ``Yellowstone Crab,'' representing the
landlocked state of Wyoming, skittered over the end of a 16-foot
plywood ramp ahead of crabs representing 43 other states to win the
crustacean version of the run for the roses.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CALGARY, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Calgary Flames will be going where no
NHL team has gone before when they leave Monday night for a
preseason tour that includes four games in the Soviet Union. But
they're not going overseas empty-handed.
   Packed among the 400 rolls of tape, 200 pucks and 57 pairs of
skates the defending Stanley Cup champions are lugging along will be
100 pounds of pasta and plenty of sauce to go with it.
   North American-style breakfast foods, granola bars and other
snacks also will be on the menu.
   ``A lot of people have been concerned about the food,'' said
assistant general manager Doug Risebrough. ``A lot of that stretches
from earlier visits to Russia. We're not going over there with a
self-containing idea. We're going to Russia and basically be
Russians for 11 days.''
   Except at mealtime.
   The pasta and sauce will be used for pregame meals and the Flames
are taking their own breakfast foods due to a concern about the lack
of cereals and eggs.
   ``We think if our players are given a similar breakfast to what
they are used to here, that will help the transition,'' Risebrough
said. ``As for the pregame meal, it's just because we're more
comfortable with what we know.''
   The Flames and Washington Capitals are the first two NHL teams
ever to travel to the Soviet Union. Both will play four games
against Soviet teams before returning home to complete their
exhibition schedule.
</TEXT>
