<FIRST>u i AM-Auschwitz-Text     09-03 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auschwitz-Text,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cardinals Say Pact Is Binding</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Auschwitz-Convent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a text of the statement issued Sunday in
Paris by three Roman Catholic cardinals who negotiated a 1987
agreement to move a convent away from the Auschwitz death camp. It
was translated from French by The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   If the Jewish delegation at the Geneva meetings, led by Mr. Theo
Klein, then president of the European Jewish Congress, is ``not
competent,'' who would be?
   And if four cardinals, including the archbishop of Krakow, are
not qualified to represent the Catholic side, who might be?
   The Auschwitz camp is in the Krakow diocese. According to church
law, its archbishop has full authority there. The cardinals who
accompanied him belong to nations who, in the West, were among the
chief victims of the Hitler barbarism.
   These accords were patiently and loyally negotiated over two
years. The Catholic signatories promised that the financing would
not fall on the Krakow diocese and still less on Poland.
   Cardinal Glemp could only have been speaking for himself in
talking of a renegotiation of the Geneva accords. Particularly since
until now he has always let it be known that Cardinal Macharski was
solely responsible and that the Polish Conference of Bishops, on
March 9, 1989, had committed itself in turn by giving its support to
the realization of this accord.
   The signed engagements must be carried out: they recognize the
legitimacy of the Auschwitz Carmel at Oswiecim, outside the
perimeter of the concentration camp which UNESCO, in consideration
of its ``exceptional universal value,'' has placed on the list of
``world cultural heritage'' in October 1979 at the request of the
Polish government then in place.
   Signed:
   Cardinal Albert Decourtray, chairman of the Catholic delegation
   Cardinal Godfried Danneels, archbishop of Mechelen-Brussels
   Cardinal Jean-Marie Lustiger, archbishop of Paris
</TEXT>
</DOC>
