<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-89 1658EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Millionaire'sMall     09-03 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Millionaire's Mall,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chic Shops, Valet Parking, Concierges: Upscale Spenders Can Have
it All</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stephen Karp's tony new shopping center is
more Maserati than Cadillac. The $50 million Atrium is opulent and
flashy, but in a way tailored to attract sophisticated, upscale
spenders.
   ``It's not for the K mart shopper,'' the mall magnate says. This
is an all-frills enterprise, adds Karp, designed to provide his
clients with the services he says they want most.
   The Atrium features doormen, valet parking, a concierge, a coat
check, tailors and even a personal shopper for those who don't have
the time to browse.
   Inside the 3-acre, nine-story granite complex off busy Route 9
are such stores as Abercrombie &amp; Fitch, The Limited,
Williams-Sonoma, Victoria's Secret and Godiva Chocolatier.
   As close as across the street are malls featuring many of the
same stores as well as such modish retailers as Bloomingdale's,
Brooks Brothers, Tiffany's, Laura Ashley, Ralph Lauren and Neiman
Marcus.
   But Atrium officials claim there's nothing else like it anywhere
in the nation. New York's flashy Trump Tower may have the same pink
marble and brass, but try finding all the personal services, they
say.
   ``The personalization makes the customers feel important,'' said
General Manager Judith Tripaldi. ``And if you raise a person's level
of self-esteem they feel good and come back.''
   The Atrium team has made a science of climbing into the psyches
of prospective clients, mainly affluent residents of this Boston
suburb.
   Karp and his partners at New England Development Co., which owns
14 regional malls, came to this latest venture armed with years of
experience and reams of market research.
   ``The demographics here are among the top in the United States,''
Karp said. ``Price is only the third or fourth most important
priority to these customers. Service is the thing.''
   And not just any service. Karp says his clients want efficiency
and sunny salespeople, but they also want something more, a certain
je ne sais quoi.
   ``This market has an international flavor,'' he said. ``They have
a lot of identification with European labels and ... with New York.''
   Janice Colley identifies with New York. The Westchester County
resident was in the Boston area staying with friends and decided to
stop by for the Atrium's grand opening.
   She loved the azaleas and Greek revival columns, but wondered
about the dollars and sense of it all. She'd just seen a globe her
family would love, but the $4,500 pricetag was out of this world.
   ``I'd rather go where you can get the best value for your
money,'' she said. ``I look at all this marble and think to myself
it's going to cost a lot to keep it clean.''
   Jody Martin, a managing partner at Stillerman Jones &amp; Co., an
Indianapolis market research firm, said K marts and other discount
outlets are phenomenally successful because their prices are low and
everyone knows it.
   ``In mainstream America valet parking is not proven to be very
critical to choosing a (shopping) center,'' Martin said in a
telephone interview. ``They want parking, restrooms, stores open
late, a post office, bank machine ... Day-to-day kinds of
necessities rather than luxuries.''
   K mart spokeswoman Leslie Kota said research indicated 50 percent
of all American shoppers, including those from upper income groups,
frequent the discount chain's 2,100 stores, which had an income last
year of $27.3 billion.
   Esther Felix and Sophie Richmond, who describe themselves as
``serious'' shoppers, were aglow last week with the Atrium's
architecture, pleasant security guards and glorious bathrooms.
   ``It's in exquisite taste and I love the luxury.'' Richmond said.
``They're making all the right moves and I can hardly wait until
Henri Bendel's arrives.''
   Bendel's, the New York department store, is one of several still
setting up. All the Atrium's retailers were scheduled to open by
February and Karp said he expected to begin turning a profit shortly
thereafter.
   ``Developers from all over the world are coming to look at what
we're doing here,'' he said. ``We've got a five-star hotel
mentality.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
