<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-03 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Darken Midwest And Southeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms and showers were scattered across the Midwest and
the Southeast on Sunday, but most of the rest of the nation enjoyed
a sunny Labor Day weekend.
   The rain spread across western and central Minnesota, Iowa,
southeast Nebraska, northeast Kansas and extreme northwestern
Missouri.
   Thunderstorms developing ahead of a cold front crossing the
Dakotas produced golf ball-size hail north of Bowlus, Minn., and
1-inch hail hail at Battle Lake, Minn.
   A second system of showers and thunderstorms moved into the
Southeast over southern and central Georgia, coastal South Carolina
and Florida.
   Showers and thunderstorms also developed over parts of Arizona,
soaking the Phoenix area with more than an inch of rain overnight. A
few showers dampened southeastern Oklahoma and southwestern Arkansas.
   Fair to partly sunny skies prevailed across the rest of the
nation.
   Heavier rainfall totals for the six-hour period ending at 2 p.m.
EDT included 1.13 inches at Albany, Ga., 1.1 inches at Fargo, N.D.,
and .97 inches at Lincoln, Neb.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 57
degrees at Lewistown, Mont., and Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 105
degrees at Blythe, Calif.
   The low for the nation Sunday morning was 28 degrees at Truckee,
Calif.
   Record high temperatures for the day included 96 degrees in Port
Arthur, Texas, breaking the record of 95 set in 1980. The
thermometer reached 98 in Brownsville, tying a 69-year-old record.
   The forecast for Labor Day called for showers and thunderstorms
from the upper and middle Mississippi Valley across eastern portions
of the central Plains into Oklahoma, and from the southern Atlantic
Coast states and Florida to the eastern half of the Gulf Coast
region. Skies were expected to be partly cloudy over Washington
state, with sunny skies forecast for most of the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures were expected in the 60s in much of New
England; the 90s from the Florida Panhandle across the lower
Mississippi Valley, the southern Plains and the southern half of New
Mexico; and near 100 degrees from central Texas to the Rio Grande
valley, with highs from 100 to 110 degrees in the desert Southwest
and interior valleys of California. Highs were expected in the 70s
and 80s over the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
