<FIRST>r a AM-FatalCrash     09-03 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fatal Crash,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Teens Die When Car Plunges Into Ravine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT IMRIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLAND, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car full of teen-agers who may have been
fleeing a party raided by police missed a stone bridge and plunged
into a shallow creek, killing six students from a rural high school,
authorities said Sunday.
   The five boys and one girl, all believed to be between 15 and 17,
may have been dead for up to 20 hours before the car was found,
police said. The car went off a gravel road, missed the bridge and
went down a ravine, landing in the creek partially submerged on its
side.
   The accident was discovered by a boy walking along the road about
6 p.m. Saturday, but authorities said they were checking reports of
a loud crash as early as 10 p.m. Friday.
   ``There's a chance they were there for some time,'' Brown County
Sheriff's Capt. William Craig said. ``Where they ended up, the car
wasn't visible from the road.'' The victims' identities were being
withheld Sunday.
   School Superintendent Larry Lark confirmed all they were all
students at Wrightstown High School. Holland is an incorporated town
within Wrightstown, a rural community of 1,020 residents about 15
miles south of Green Bay.
   Principal Jack Lewis called the victims ``typical teen-age kids
for this area'' and said he did not know where the victims had been
or were going before the accident.
   But a group of teen-agers gathered outside St. Paul Roman
Catholic Church in Wrightstown on Sunday morning said they had known
the victims from school and heard they had left a party that police
raided.
   ``They all took off before it got raided,'' said Melanie
Buechler, 14.
   Deputy Sheriff Mike Schroll confirmed on Sunday that police had
broken up a party five or six miles from the crash site, but he did
not know if the victims had been at the party.
   To help grieving classmates, school officials alerted a team of
counselors assembled 11 months ago when five elementary-school girls
died in a car-pedestrian accident in nearby Pulaski.
</TEXT>
