<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0687 09-03 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0687,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Broadens Orders on Shooting Masked Palestinians</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with death of second Israeli soldier,
Amman denying Arab crossed from Jordan; No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops will be able to use live
ammunition ``day or night'' to stop masked Palestinian suspects
resisting arrest in the occupied territories, Defense Minister
Yitzhak Rabin said Sunday.
   Late Sunday, a second Israeli soldier died of wounds received in
a gun battle with an alleged infiltrator from Jordan Saturday, an
army spokesman said.
   The army said the 27-year-old soldier died from a bullet wound in
the head. His death came hours after the burial of a 25-year-old
soldier who was also killed in the clash. The Palestinian, who was
not identified, was slain by Israeli forces.
   In Amman, a senior official said Sunday that Jordan has found no
evidence the guerrilla had crossed from Jordanian territory.
   The strengthened security measure is directed at Arab youth who
enforce orders from the underground leaders of the 20-month-old
Palestinian uprising. Usually wearing masks and operating at night,
they sometimes attack and kill other Arabs suspected of
collaborating with the Israeli occupation.
   A Palestinian activist said the order will lead to more
Palestinian being shot.
   Defense Ministry spokesman Eitan Haber said that in the past,
soldiers were restricted to using plastic bullets against the
suspects after they refused to stop on order and after a warning
shot was fired. But other sources said on condition of anonymity
that firing live ammunition at masked suspects had been allowed at
night.
   In his announcement on Israel radio, Rabin said the new measure
was needed to crack down on Palestinian militants who are
terrorizing the population.
   He spoke after Palestinian enforcers killed one suspected
collaborator and wounded another in an attack with knives and
hatchets.
   An Arab journalist reported seeing the mutilated body of
25-year-old Riyad Abbas Salem Nasrallah on a Gaza City street
Sunday. Awaiting medical treatment next to the body was 18-year-old
Raed Majed Husseini. He had been beaten and stabbed.
   A crowd gathered as the body was put into an ambulance and
shouted ``death to collaborators!'' Other witnesses said some
passers-by spit and threw tomatoes.
   Masked Palestinians are blamed for most of the 105 Arabs killed
by other Arabs during the uprising. At least 557 Palestinians have
been killed by Israelis.
   ``Israeli Defense Forces will receive in the next few days
permission to use live fire to stop suspects who are wearing
masks,'' Rabin said. He said they would be allowed to do so ``day or
night.''
   Assad Saftawi, an elementary school principal in the Gaza Strip
and a prominent activist, predicted the new orders would lead to
more Palestinians being shot by soldiers and ``more enmity.''
   ``This is a serious crackdown on the intefadeh,'' he said, using
the Arab word for ``uprising.'' ``Political and military leaders in
Israel talk about a political solution for the intefadeh, but in
practice what they do contradicts what they say.''
   In other comments on Israel radio, Rabin also warned Jordan that
Israel would not tolerate attacks on its territory from Jordan.
   He spoke after the clash between Israeli soldiers and a
Palestinian guerrilla near the Jordan River. On March 17, an Israeli
soldier was also killed, and the two attackers fled back into Jordan.
   ``Jordan must find a way to prevent fire or infiltration from its
border if it wants ... to have neighborly relations with us,'' he
said.
   In Amman, a high government official denied the Palestinian
entered Israel from Jordan.
   ``We have no proof that a civilian crossed the cease-fire line,''
the official said on condition of anonymity. ``Usually when someone
crosses, we could figure it out. Either he crosses a certain fence
or sometimes (leaves) a footprint ... There's nothing.''
   In another development, Palestinian sources estimated 20,000
Palestinians crossed into Israel to work Sunday using new
Israeli-issued identity cards. Normally, nearly 50,000 go to work in
Israel.
   Leaders of the Palestinian uprising have tried to keep residents
from using the cards.
</TEXT>
