<FIRST>r a AM-Kaifu-NewEngland     09-03 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kaifu-New England,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Prime Minister Tours Land of Pilgrim's Pride</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BXF1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVE EPSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PLYMOUTH, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese Prime Minister Toshiku Kaifu
stepped out of high-tech Boston and back in time Sunday, touring the
thatched huts of Plimoth Plantation and a replica of the Mayflower.
   The Prime Minister and his wife, Sachiyo, joined a group of
singers dressed as Pilgrims in a verse of the 100th Psalm, rode an
ox cart and sampled an old-fashioned spice loaf during a visit to a
reproduction of a 17th century New England colony in this coastal
community.
   In a brief news conference, Kaifu, 58, harked back to his first
visit to the United States 27 years ago, when he was first elected
to the Japanese Parliament.
   ``Simply, my impression was that this is a huge, vast country,''
he said through a translator.
   Other visitors to Plimoth Plantation snapped photos and waved as
the Prime Minister wound through the dirt streets of the early
colonial town.
   Earlier in the day, the prime minister visited Boston's Museum of
Fine Arts where he toured the Asiatic, Impressionist and Copley
galleries.
   At one point on the tour a member of his entourage gave Kaifu a
$1 bill, which the prime minister held up to compare to a portrait
of George Washington.
   At Fenway Park, Kaifu and his entourage were greated at a side
gate by Boston Red Sox general manager Lou Gorman and dined with the
club's owner, Jean Yawkey, in Fenway's 600 club.
   Kaifu and his wife received a warm welcome from the Boston fans
as he took off his suit coat and donned a Red Sox cap to throw up
the ceremonial first pitch to Boston catcher Rich Gedman.
   Later, Kaifu returned upstairs to the club's private box to watch
the game with Gorman.
   The prime minister's trip comes soon after his ascension to
Japan's top political post and is designed, in part, to lend
legitimacy to his new administration.
   Kaifu was named prime minister last month after his predecessors
in the ruling party suffered a series of political and sex scandals.
   Kaifu, who served twice as Japan's educational minister, also
visited Harvard University and received a souvenir T-shirt at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
   The prime minister wanted to emphasize the top priority he gives
to the relationship between the United States and Japan in the
educational sphere, said Richard Winslow, an adviser at the Japanese
Consulate.
   Kaifu arrived in Boston on Saturday and discussed trade issues
and education with Gov. Michael S. Dukakis and leaders of local
universities.
   Kaifu came straight from Washington, where he met Friday with
President Bush on the second leg of his 5-day tour of the United
States.
   After the meeting with Dukakis, the Prime Minister held a dinner
for the area's leading academicians. The presidents of Harvard
University, Boston University, The University of Massachusetts and
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology were invited, as well as
several East Asia scholars.
   The prime minister is scheduled to fly to Mexico on Monday.
</TEXT>
