<HEAD>Opposition Calls for Peaceful Resistance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 people shouting ``Down with
Noriega!'' gathered outside a church Sunday, and opposition leader
Guillermo Endara urged them to peacefully resist the new civilian
government installed by the general.
   ``We are going to dedicate ourselves to resisting this military
dictatorship of Manuel Antonio Noriega to the end,'' said Endara,
who international observers said won the May 7 elections in a
landslide.
   The government annulled that election.
   On Thursday, the Council of State, considered to be controlled by
Noriega, named Panama's comptroller, Francisco Rodriguez Poveda, as
president.
   Endara faced supporters outside the Christ the King Roman
Catholic Church after attending Mass with his running mates in the
election, Ricardo Arias Calderon and Guillermo Ford.
   Endara said the opposition to the government would continue, but
``this resistance is going to be peaceful,'' he said. ``With prayer,
God is not ever going to abandon the Panamanian people and soon,
very soon, he will give us justice and freedom,''
   Supporters chanted ``Down with Noriega!'' and ``You feel it, you
feel it, Endara is the president!''
   The meeting was the first public gathering by the opposition
since Rodriguez, 50, a high school friend of Noriega, was sworn as
provisional president on Friday.
   The opposition refused to form a junta with the civilian
government and the military. A day before the term of acting
president Manuel Solis Palma expired, Rodriguez was picked to be
president.
   The provisional government is to appoint a 41-member legislative
commission to replace the assembly, whose term also expired Friday.
   Rodriguez and the Council of State have said the holding of new
elections will depend on whether the United States lifts economic
sanctions imposed to pressure Noriega to step down as chief of the
Defense Forces.
   The United States has frozen about $300 million in Panamanian
assets and ha imposed trade sanctions that include a ban on any
payments to the Panamanian government.
   U.S. Embassy said Friday the American government is compiling a
list of companies and individuals associated with Noriega and may
block them from doing business with Americans.
   The United States began urging Noriega to step down after he was
indicted by two Florida grand juries in February 1988 on charges of
drug trafficking. Noriega denies the charges.
</TEXT>
