<FIRST>u i AM-Vietnam-Bank     09-03 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam-Bank,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam Sets Up Import-Export Bank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam has established an import-export
bank financed by shareholders, a report seen Sunday said.
   The initial capital of the Vietnam Export-Import Bank is $28
million, divided into 250,000 shares.
   The bank was described in a Radio Hanoi broadcast as ``a
partnership corporation doing business in money and credit, and
providing banking services to serve production, processing of export
goods and export-import activities.''
   The radio said that as of late August, 130 units and 2,300
individuals had registered to buy 32,000 shares. Shareholders can
pay in Vietnamese or foreign currencies, precious metals or stones
or merchandise qualified for export.
   ``With a view to mobilizing more capital, the Vietnam
Export-Import Bankhas extended the period for buying shares to
mid-September,'' said the Radio Hanoi report, which was broadcast
Thursday and monitored and made available by a Western embassy.
   Vietnam is expanding its economic ties with Western and
non-communist Asian nations and is trying to attract foreign
investors to stimulate its poor economic performance in recent years.
