<FIRST>r a AM-SailingFamily     09-03 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sailing Family,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple Returns Home After Eight-Year Sail Around The World</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX5 of Sept. 2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stan and Caren Sutton were a romantic young
couple when they sank their life savings into a homemade fiberglass
sailboat for a voyage around the world.
   More than eight years later _ or 55 countries, 58,000 miles, and
two children later _ the Suttons sailed under the Golden Gate to
return home on Saturday.
   ``To be honest, it's a lot of work _ and a lot of fun,'' Stan
Sutton said. ``Anybody can do it. Just go for it.''
   The couple and their two daughters born during the family's
odyssey were welcomed at the St. Francis Yacht Club by dozens of
family and friends and a proclamation of welcome from the city.
   The Suttons, sailing novices who first shared the dream of
traveling around the world while high school sweethearts, started
building their 43-foot sailing yawl, the Marinka, 14 years ago. The
couple sold their possessions and sailed out beyond the Golden Gate
in March 1981.
   Three days before their scheduled departure, Caren Sutton learned
she was pregnant.
   ``She was very nervous about that. They had to reconsider the
trip. They thought about it for a long time and decided to go,''
said her mother, Holly Anderson.
   Caren Sutton, after a first leg of the voyage that gave new
meaning to the term morning sickness, gave birth to Elizabeth, now
7, in Hawaii. Jennifer, now 5, was born in Pago Pago.
   ``It was my husband's dream and I just went along with it,''
Caren Sutton said. ``He did everything, from navigating to operating
the radio. ...I take orders very well, cook and take care of the
children.''
   But her husband said his wife underestimated her role and called
her a ``trouper.''
   The family weathered hurricanes and visited such lands as
Indonesia, Thailand, Sri Lanka, Egypt, Turkey, Tunisia, the Canary
Islands and Panama, Stan Sutton said. Not all was idyllic, however:
The Marinka survived eight storms at sea, including four hurricanes
in 1983.
   Throughout the years, Holly Anderson and Stan Sutton's mother,
Natalie Sutton, visited their children and grandchildren in various
ports around the world and kept in constant touch with them, often
by ham radio.
   While happy he lived his lifelong dream, Stan Sutton was glad to
be home.
   ``These are our freinds and family,'' he said. ``This is the
best. To be back from it all is great.''
   The Suttons also are looking forward to _ for them _ a novel way
of life.
   ``The biggest adventure of all I can think of now is buying a
house, mowing the lawn and watching the kids grow _ doing everything
everybody else is doing, and taking a hot shower every day,'' Stan
Sutton said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890903-0063 </DOCNO>
