<FIRST>u i AM-SriLanka     09-03 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Doesn't Want Human Rights Groups In Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa said
Sunday he would not allow international human rights groups into Sri
Lanka to investigate alleged rights abuses.
   Also Sunday, an Information Department statement said 24 people
were killed over the weekend by Sinhalese radicals from the People's
Liberation Front, an ultranationalist guerrilla group seeking to
overthrow the government.
   The victims included five women relatives of security force
personnel, 12 civilians, five soldiers, a doctor and a postal
official, the statement said. It gave no further details.
   Premadasa's declaration regarding human rights came after he met
with a six-member opposition group called the Committee of
Parliamentarians of the Opposition for Fundamental and Human Rights.
   The group urged the president to safeguard human rights, the
statement said. Premadasa said the government was not prepared to
permit international human rights groups, including Amnesty
International, to visit the country.
   He told opposition leaders that ``human rights is not the
preserve of one party or group,'' according to the statement.
   Opposition politicians and human rights groups have accused the
military and pro-government vigilante groups of killing hundreds of
civilians suspected of sympathizing with Sinhalese radicals.
   At least 1,222 people have been killed since June 20, when
Premadasa imposed a state of emergency and gave security forces
special powers.
   In mid-August, the London-based human rights group Amnesty
International appealed to the Sri Lankan government to stem what it
called the rising tide of killings, torture, disappearances and
detentions perpetrated by its forces.
   The government denies the charges and says Sinhalese extremists
are responsible for most of the 5,000 killings reported since the
front began its campaign two years ago.
   The front claims the government made too many concessions to
Tamil secessionists in an India-brokered peace accord of June, 1987.
It also protests the presence of Indian peacekeeping soldiers,
deployed in the northeast under the accord to disarm Tamil militants.
   The front, in letters sent to Colombo newspapers Sunday, accused
the government of killing more than 5,000 people in the last two
years.
   The letters, signed by the group's leader, Rohana Wijeweera,
called upon opposition political parties to unite, saying, ``people
know who is doing the killings and what is taking place in the
country.''
   The statement was the front's first known appeal to political
parties.
   It also warned that people must be ``prepared to make sacrifices
to save their motherland,'' indicating they might enforce another
strike after last week's successful work stoppage.
   Sri Lankan businessmen say a series of radical-enforced strikes
have crippled the country's economy.
   The country's ethnic troubles surfaced in 1983 when the Tamil
minority began demanding a separate nation in the northeast. The
armed insurrection has claimed 11,000 lives, according to government
figures.
   The Tamil community, which comprises 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16
million people, allege discrimination by the majority Sinhalese in
jobs and education. Sinhalese are mostly Buddhists and Tamils are
mostly Hindus.
</TEXT>
