<FIRST>u i AM-Non-Aligned     09-03 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Non-Aligned,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ghadafi, Other Leaders Arrive for Non-Aligned Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State and government leaders from 102
nations are expected for the opening Monday of the ninth summit of
non-aligned nations that will be held at Belgrade's Sava conference
center.
   Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi arrived Sunday and issued a
statement saying, ``If the movement does not modernize, it can be
considered dead.''
   Col. Gadhafi sent in advance a Bedouin tent and four camels and
at a news conference in the tent he suggested the kidnapping of
Westerners in Lebanon was in response to Western intervention in the
Middle East.
   ``I believe Western countries should withdraw from the Middle
East and not intervene in the internal affairs (of those countries)
or else their citizens shall be victims,'' he said.
   He described the Western hostages held by extremists in Lebanon
as ``innocent victims due to the intervention of their respective
governments'' in the Middle East.
   Gadhafi was asked about the possible release of the hostages and
he said if he could help ``I would never delay'' efforts. But he
then added, ``If we knew who kidnapped them we could talk to'' the
abductors.
   Gadhafi, wearing a silk robe, black cape and white turban, spoke
through an interpreter at the news conference that began at 11 p.m.
   He said, ``We do not recognize any U.S. role in any of the
respective (Mideast) countries,'' and that also was true of France
and all other Western nations.
   Eight Americans are among 16 foreign hostages held in Lebanon.
Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The Associated
Press, has been held the longest. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   Gadhafi's tent was erected in a park in Belgrade's Dedinje suburb.
   Yugoslav President Janez Drnovsek, in an interview published
Saturday, said streamlining the non-aligned movement is the key
issue of the four-day conference. His foreign minister, Budimir
Loncar, said the movement must modernize its political activities.
   For the first time, the movement of leftist, centrist and
conservative leaders is scheduled to deal with human rights.
   After two days of talks, foreign ministers from member countries
early Sunday adopted a main conference document for consideration by
the summit.
   The draft refers to the ``struggle against imperialism,
colonialism, neo-colonialism, racism, apartheid and all forms of
domination.''
   But the Palestine Liberation Organization failed to have included
in the document a condemnation of Zionism.
</TEXT>
