<FIRST>r a AM-Cowboys-Owners     09-03 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cowboys-Owners,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDIC Looks to Sell its Share of the Cowboys</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   FORT WORTH _ The Dallas Cowboys are living up to their billing as
``America's team'' _ at least 12 percent of the club is.
   A chunk of the NFL franchise has fallen into the hands of the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. and officials are looking for a
buyer, according to a Fort Worth newspaper.
   The government gained a stake in the Cowboys when the FDIC helped
NCNB Corp. of Charlotte, N.C. take over First Republic Bank Corp. of
Dallas in July 1988.
   First Republic Bank took control of the shares after S. Foster
Yancey Jr., L. Bradley Camp and J.L. Huffines, all of whom were
limited partners in the franchise, encountered financial problems in
their real estate businesses.
   The bank foreclosed and collected the shares, which were pledged
as collateral on loans.
   After the takeover, the bank assumed the name NCNB Texas. The
Cowboys share sale is being handled as part of the bank's agreement
to manage the $5 billion asset pool for the government.
   ``We're certainly looking for a bidder, bank spokesman Joe Bowles
told the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. ``We are actively looking for a
buyer.''
   Although the sale price NCNB is seeking is uncertain, sources say
the 12 percent share is worth about $7.2 million, the Fort Worth
newspaper reported.
   That figure is based on H.R. ``Bum'' Bright's sale of his 40
percent general parternship of the Cowboys to Arkansas millionaire
Jerry Jones, who paid $60 million this year to gain controlling
interest of the National Football League team.
   Jones says he controls a 56 percent holding, with 51 percent in
his name and five percent in the name of associate Mike McCoy. The
limited partners are Ed Smith Jr, with 27 percent; Arthur ``Buddy''
Temple, with five percent; and the government, with 12 percent.
   The NFL has to approve any new partner before the government can
complete a sale.
   Jones has told the Star-Telegram that he has ``no plans at this
time'' to acquire the government's stake. Other shareholders said
they plan to keep their shares because investing in the Cowboys is a
good investment.
   ``With new TV rights, a big gate and new radio contract, the
Cowboys could be profitable,'' said John Veatch, managing director
of Salomon Brothers' Dallas operations, who handled Bright's sale of
the team to Jones.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
