<HEAD>Two Snowbird Stunt Jets Crash; One Pilot Feared Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos CPT5, CPT9</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with missing pilot identified,
aerobatic teams suspends performances. Picks up 13th pvs, `Team members...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two jets from the Snowbirds aerobatic team crashed
into Lake Ontario during an air show Sunday after apparently
striking each other, authorities said. One pilot was feared dead and
the other parachuted to safety.
   Divers searched Sunday night for Capt. Shayne Antaya, 24, of
Stratford, Ontario, who went down with his plane and was feared dead.
   Maj. Dan Dempsey of Edmonton, the 36-year-old commander of the
Canadian Forces precision flying team, safely ejected and was
treated briefly at the hospital for facial cuts and leg burns before
being released.
   Witnesses along the Toronto waterfront reported Dempsey's
parachute opened just before a there was a loud explosion and one
plane plunged into the lake within a few hundreds yard of the shore
under clear skies.
   At a news conference Sunday night, Col. Claude Thibault said
Antaya's wife, mother, brother and sister were among thousands of
people watching the show from the shore.
   ``There were four aircraft heading down and three heading up,''
said Oliver Gross of Bramalea, Ontario, who watched the accident
through binoculars. ``It looked like one wingtip hit the other one's
tail, belly to belly.
   ``The one going down went straight into the lake. The other one
attempted to gain altitude and began to swerve off to the right
before it exploded. We saw the pilot eject and the parachute drop.
No pilot came out of the other one.''
   Owen James of Toronto, one of thousands of horrified onlookers,
said, ``The one aircraft just literally disappeared into a complete
ball of flame and black smoke.
   ``They were flying in a fairly close formation, operating away
from the main team.''
   The accident occurred about 1:45 p.m. on the second day of a
three-day air show at the Canadian National Exhibition held along
the waterfront west ot downtown.
   The pilots were performing a stunt called an upward-downward bomb
burst. Canada's nine-member military stunt team performs at more
than 60 air shows throughout North America each year.
   Col. Thibault said the Snowbirds ``are filled with a sense of
loss'' and had suspended future shows.
   Team members fly the CT-114 Tutor, a single-engine jet trainer
used by the military as its basic training aircraft. The plane is
manufactured by Canadair Ltd. of Montreal and has a maximum speed of
nearly 500 mph.
   The Snowbirds' performance includes at least 30 separate
maneuvers.
   Officially known as the 431 Air Demonstration Squadron, it is a
permanent unit of the Canadian Forces based in Moosejaw,
Saskatchewan,
   Before Sunday's tragedy, the Showbirds had three air-show
accidents in which two pilots were killed during the 19 years of
precision flying.
   On Aug. 28, 1988, three jets from the Italian stunt team Freece
Tricolori crashed during an air show at Ramstein U.S. Air Base in
Ramstein, West Germany, killing 70 people.
</TEXT>
