<HEAD>488 Kurdish Refugees Leave Camp To Return To Iraq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUS, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of 488 Kurdish refugees left their
camp in this southeastern province to return to Iraq voluntarily,
the semi-official Anatolia news agency reported Sunday.
   The agency quoted Mus Governor Adil Yazar as saying the group
left the camp in three trucks and five buses Saturday night and
would leave the country through the Habur border gate.
   A group of 380 Kurdish refugees returned to Iraq last month.
   The Kurds are an ethnic minority of 20 million living in Turkey,
Iran, and Iraq and small enclaves of 500,000 each in Syria and the
Soviet Union.
   The Iraqi government has been accused of forcibly evacuating
thousands of Kurds from their homes, razing towns in the northern
Kurdish homeland and resettling Kurds in the south of the country.
   The government says the resettlement is to improve life for the
impoverished Kurds.
   Last year, Iraqis dropped poison gas on the Kurdish town of
Halabja, killing an estimated 4,000 civilians. The Kurds claim
thousands more were killed in similar chemical weapons attacks last
fall.
   Following the attacks by the Iraqi army, about 60,000 Kurds fled
to Turkey. Some have since gone to Iran and a few thousand have
returned to Iraq.
   About 40,000 remain in tent camps and crowded apartment houses in
southeast Turkey.
</TEXT>
