<FIRST>u a AM-AirCollision     09-03 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Air Collision,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helicopter, Small Plane Collide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUMA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commercial helicopter collided with a small
plane above a rural subdivision Sunday night, killing all three
people aboard both aircraft and scattering debris over the
neighborhood, authorities said.
   Two people in the helicopter and the woman pilot of the
single-engine plane were killed in the crash about 6:45 p.m., about
a mile from the Houma-Terrebonne Airport, said police Capt. John
Dixon.
   ``I heard the crash. It was a loud bang, like two cars hitting
real hard,'' said Ken Domangue, a part-time photographer for the
Houma Courier newspaper. ``Then I walked around the trees and I saw
what looked like one fairly large plane coming down. Then they
separated, and one went one way and one went the other.''
   ``They were smoking as they fell. When they hit the ground, there
was a puff of black smoke and then flames,'' Domangue said.
   ``No houses were hit, but debris was scattered all across the
neighborhood _ helicopter blades, a seat cushion a couple of hundred
feet away. Registration papers from the Cessna fell in my front
yard,'' he said.
   The victims' identities were not immediately known, but a company
official acknowledged one of the aircraft belonged to Petroleum
Helicopters Inc., which serves the offshore oil industry.
   Petroleum Helicopters Inc. vice president-general manager Carl
Dougherty said the helicopter, which crashed soon after takeoff, was
only on a three-mile flight.
   Dixon said the helicopter crashed and burned in an intersection
just outside Houma's southern city limits and the plane crashed into
a tree, but there were neither injuries nor damages on the ground.
   Dixon said the collision was being investigated by the Terrebonne
Parish Sheriff's Department, but neither the sheriff nor any of his
employees would comment immediately.
   Dougherty said he would not identify the helicopter's passengers
until their relatives are notified. He said National Transportation
Safety Board investigators were expected to arrive Monday morning.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
