<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--BeachedWhale     09-03 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Beached Whale,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baby Whale Washes Ashore</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A baby sperm whale, rarely found in the
Gulf of Mexico, was being cared for Sunday at Sea Arama Marineworld
after the whale beached itself near Sabine Pass.
   The 13-foot, 900-pound calf was found Saturday on the Bolivar
Peninsula, said Marineworld spokeswoman Christy Benson. ``It is only
a baby, about a week old,'' she said.
   Voluneers helped hoist it onto a flatbed truck, where it was
covered with wet cloths and sunscreen for the trip to the aquarium.
   Ms. Benson said 99 percent of all mammals that beach themselves
are dying. However, the whale seemed to be doing pretty well.
   ``When we determine that he is healthy, we will return him to the
sea,'' she told the Galveston News.
   However, the whale had not been weaned and there was no sign of
its mother. So Marineworld experts were feeding it with a nutrient
solution.
   Fully grown, sperm whales can reach 50 feet in length.
</TEXT>
